data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is a no-op. Here's the full migration:

## The Problem

| Removed API | Why it fails in .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `ThreadAbortException` catch | Never thrown — dead code |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | No-op / obsolete |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // CancellationTokenSource enforces the timeout cooperatively
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            // Task.Run schedules work on the thread pool (no manual Thread needed)
            var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

            // WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException if timeout expires
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## If the `Func<T>` itself is long-running

The above stops *waiting*, but the work may keep running in the background since cancellation is **cooperative**. To make the work actually stop, pass the token through:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

Callers then check the token at regular intervals:

```csharp
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // cooperative checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Solution |
|---|---|
| Work keeps running after "timeout" | `Task.Run` fire-and-forget won't stop the delegate. Pass `CancellationToken` into the work and check it. |
| Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource` | Always `using` — leaking it causes timer leaks. |
| Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| Calling unmodifiable blocking code (e.g., third-party) | No cooperative fix possible. Move to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout. |
| Replacing `Thread.Sleep` inside work | Use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` instead — it wakes immediately on cancellation. |

The fundamental shift: .NET Framework allowed **preemptive** termination (abort injected an exception anywhere). .NET 8 requires **cooperative** cancellation — your code must voluntarily check the token and exit.
